London Henry Maynard
th
th
S. mij last to you was on the 25„ curitt sence recd. yd of 13 ditto by
which you hope to provide the 6N silver marck I could wish to have
5 peeces & then wee will allow him more time for more peeces, so pray
do what you can to persuade him the clothier there unto: for my reputation
layes on itt bij the goods fathers Jesuits, haveing so fait fully promiseditt
I observe the invoyce of the resting spanish cloathes, which I had exspected
all of a drap cullour & finde butt N. 690 „ 91 & 94 as I could
wish all had been, whoever inclosed are pattarnes for one packe
more of spanish cloathes, which you please to provide att the advantidge
of the markett. I have given you creditt for mij share in the bales
N. 26 „ 27„ 28„ 29 & 30 god send them all safe over I have no news yett
of white, & want much the pack N. 20 because I have sold itt upon
the pattarnes, I was in hopes that the pbale of kersies 1½ lenght should
have been aboard smith, butt now do exspect itt with pindar mij
thanckes for yd care in providing the packing press and the frises of
which do exspect yd advise p next mij remises were accepted which
is well: you have drawne £500: on the keires of madm: bouwens
which I doubt not butt shall be accepted, for which shall take care as
for JP. itt can easely be that my letter to m. slaughter beared
date 10 dayes after his death, because I onely certainly knew that hewas
dead least week when I was att Brussels my self, for be fore, what
I wrott to him or not, I never saw his answer, so that they do not
concerne them selves, iust as if itt was non of their concernes
the goods lay still unsold, & I could wish to be ridd of y. aswell
as of an on advisted accompt, which stands open betwixt us so lett
mee have mr slaughters orders, for selling the cloth here would
be an over great loss, besides non of the yeallow cullours are to
be sold, so that I know not what to do, which I leave you to considder
whilst I am willing to do mr. slaughter what service I can & remaine
P.S. Receaved a letter from Antoni peeters bij which he tells mee
there is good apearence of receaving mony an london & that hewill
come here to adiust the matter of which more when & see him
these pattarnes are to provide 12 spanish clothes viz 6 under the 75t
aijard: and 6 under 8:6 ayd butt the drap cullours do not yett please mee as
I could wish, for I see here that are more lively, for such as are in the pack
N. 27 viz N. 693 and 695 are hardely vendable, beeng of a to deddish
cullour there fore peruse yd pattarne book that, you send non of said
numbers butt att least to these patt. in case you can gett non that are
more pleasant

ondon, Abram vivian
S. my last to you was on the 25: curitt then remitted you £140: in 2 bills
which I hope are come to ijd handes eve now & prove content: I have before
mee yd of 13: curitt I hope the packett N. 15 with you inclosed factory
for one packett N.16 bij John colliner from ostend which was intended
for will scawen, and is assorted, and ordered as all the goods are which
he receaves from these parts there fore lett mee have yd opinion
of the one and the other: the laces which I have here ready will
make up about 2 packetts more, and then I'll desist till further order
the peeces you send mee is putt out to be made @ 6 or 8 to yd orders and all
imaginable care shall be taken to comply exactely in all respects I shall give
you creditt for the bayes & kersies, butt yd freind must give an accompt of
what baijes in each pack, because wee ostendell the packes without
opening any, which now I can not do: as desired. lest the kersie come with
pindar with one or 2 packes of cloth & the rest with nelson, of
which yd advise whilst I remaine with kinde
In Antwerp 28 June: 1681
Lille Rich.d Southell
S. I wrott to you yeasterday & hoped sence to have seen some lines from you butt do
much wonder, to finde non, do not know what to thinck in case my remise
should be miscarried & that itt should come to handes when soever itt be, gett presentley
an attestation att the post house of such a letter delivered you, provided the £80:
should not be payd, I long to heare from you with great impatiency & remaine with
London Henry Collier
th
S. my last to you was on the 25: curitt sence non from you this day TH gave his
answer in lace composed in 27 articles. viz
s that when you drew the 2 bills, he protest and denyes that then he was in debted
to you for one forthing
2: butt to the contrarie that when you drew the bills you were indebted to him
3 and althought he knows the 2 bills were drewne up on him, yett
4 he persists to have accepted them for yd accompt onely
5 with express declaration that not withstanding the acceptance he would not pay
the same when dew
6 butt that you must give order for their satisfaction & provision by times
& that to mee as apeares bij a letter he writt you the 11 and 21 gt. 1679
7 the coppyes of which are annexed to his answer --
8 so that here ferres him self to the bills & proceeds: -
9 as apeares bij the protests that the casskepper ( hemcarres I Brickley ) hath
declared that TH should not pay for want of provision
10 that itt is true, that few dayes after he wrott you this that he went forlondon
11 were arriving att yd house hath don great compleaints with you about said
2 bills, and related the contents of his 2 last letters above mentioned
12 att which you have answered that you should give mee order to pay the 2 bills whe
13 & that & TH not in the least should be molested or troubled for them bills or valew
14 and accordinglij to which he denyes that I should have payd yd bills out-
15 of mij owne consideration, beeng to the contray true that you
16 have given order for the payement of said 2 bills and that I have
18 paijd them bills out of respect to yd order bij which he addes that I not can be
rekoned in the case as haveing power to act against him or you, neither
bij mine in dossement you or him as beeng yd bills now satisfied by yd order
so you can not proceed against him, he haveing accepted them out of respects
to you & not because he was indebted
sence all which time you never till now have made mention (alie with the rest
of said bills
yett in case you pretend he was then (when you drew) indebted, which
thought he denijes, yett is contented you should proceed up on the acctt. so all
considdered, desires the law to excuse him of ramptisation according to
7 the sentence give att this wee are to answer: where here I relate onely
the substance of his answer & shall delay to answer till wee see some
lines from you thought tis impudent all what he applyes and as
wee supose onelij to gaine time, praij endeavour to finde his 2 letters of
11 & 21 gt 79 & send mee, for if wee can make him a lyer in one, wee wil
gett him presentley downe, you may freely write him that you have seen his
answer in law, and that you wonder how he can denye in this manner
& that oneles he will comply by faire maines you will orderkers eyne
to executs, him with all vigour this is the needfull with desire that
be concealed in the bussynes be cause I am

Brussel Antonio peeters
mons. Den ul van gisteren is mij geworden, het afsterven van uwen broeder is
mij leet, eghter moet men sigh aenden wille des eere geirne onderworpen
tis noch goet hij uyt Engelant & costij gestorven is, ick hope godt sijn siele genadigh sijn
tis mij aengenaem dat ul genegen is omonse affairen tassisteren hoe eerder ul
het selve gelieft hoe liefer ick het hebbe soo ul magh overkomen alst ul gelieft
eerder omdat mons. verspoet int kort staet te vertreken naer engelant
ende hij van ul freer saligher tot assistentie van hem, was versoeght, ende also
alle mijne dingengereet sijn esser van mijntwegen nergens nae te taddeeren hebbe
bij naer ider postdagh brieven van mr slaighter die seer preseent tot betalinge soo
en sal niet antwoorde voor dat ul sal hebbe gesproeken waermede blijve
